      "titleTr": "# Editorial: Record Tourist Arrivals in Korea — The Key Now Is Spreading Benefits Across Regions\n\nSouth Korea has achieved a historic milestone in international tourism. Last year marked a record-breaking year for foreign visitor arrivals, exceeding previous highs and signaling the nation's recovery as a premier global travel destination.\n\nThis achievement reflects Korea's diverse attractions — from vibrant urban culture and cutting-edge technology to traditional heritage and natural beauty. The success of Korean cultural content on the world stage, including K-pop, K-drama, and Korean cuisine, has also played a significant role in drawing visitors.\n\nHowever, with this accomplishment comes a critical challenge. Currently, the benefits of tourism remain heavily concentrated in Seoul and a handful of major cities. The vast majority of foreign tourists follow well-trodden paths, leaving regional economies largely untouched by the tourism boom.\n\nTo ensure sustainable growth in the tourism sector, Korea must broaden the geographic distribution of visitors. This requires strategic investment in regional infrastructure, promotion of local attractions and experiences, and development of distinctive destination brands for each area.\n\nThe government and tourism industry must work together to create incentives that guide visitors beyond Seoul. By showcasing regional cultural heritage, natural attractions, and unique local experiences, Korea can transform tourism from a Seoul-centric phenomenon into a genuinely nationwide industry.\n\nThe challenge now is clear: converting record visitor numbers into equitable economic benefits across the entire nation.",
