      "bodyTr": "# Foreign Visitors to Korea Hit Record High in First Quarter\n\nForeign tourists visiting Korea in the first quarter of this year reached 4.76 million, marking an all-time high for the period. This represents a 23 percent increase from the same quarter last year. The Ministry of Culture, Sports and Tourism attributed the surge to the \"global popularity of Korean culture.\" The BTS concert at Gwanghwamun Square last month is believed to have played a significant role.\n\nThe phenomenon of Korean culture serving as a driving force for Korean tourism has become increasingly evident in recent years. According to a 2024 survey by the Korea Culture and Tourism Institute, \"Korean Wave content\" ranked first and \"Korean traditional culture\" ranked second among reasons foreign tourists became interested in Korea.\n\nEncouraging is the fact that this interest extends beyond Seoul to regional areas rich in traditional culture. According to ministry data, foreign tourists entering through provincial airports in the first quarter surged 50 percent compared to the same period last year. Many of these visitors subsequently turn their attention to regional tourism.\n\nIn the first quarter, the proportion of foreign visitors to regions reached 34.5 percent, up 3 percentage points from the previous year. Meanwhile, their regional stay duration and card spending increased by 36 percent and 27 percent respectively. While it may be premature to conclude that the nature of foreign tourism to Korea has fundamentally changed, the fact that foreign visitors are venturing into regions, staying longer, and spending more is undoubtedly encouraging.\n\nPresident Lee Jae-myung's remarks at the State Council meeting on the 14th about mobilizing local residents, small business owners, and tourism activists while providing administrative support reflected a desire to expand this trend. Accordingly, the Ministry of the Interior and Safety proposed establishing public-private tourism councils at the city and county levels, while the Ministry of Culture, Sports and Tourism expressed its commitment to supporting regional tourism activists.\n\nThe direction of public-private cooperation in actively leveraging private sector ideas is sound. However, for results to materialize, local administrative efficiency must be strengthened in areas such as transportation, infrastructure, and regulations, and political considerations that obstruct efficient decision-making must be eliminated. Tourism represents one of the crucial solutions to regional depopulation and the widening gap between the Seoul metropolitan area and non-capital regions—among Korea's",
